<A NAME="projects"></A>
<H2>Research Projects</H2>
<UL>
<li> <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/FBS/sentiment-analysis.html"> <b>Opinion Mining, Sentiment Analysis and Opinion Spam Detection</b></a> 
<ul>
<li>Book: <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/FBS/SentimentAnalysis-and-OpinionMining.pdf">Intro and Survey</a>
</ul>
<li> <b><a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/lifelong-learning.html"> Lifelong Machine Learning - Making Use of Big Data </b></a>
<ul>
<li>Also called <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/lifelong-learning.html">Continual machine Learning</a> or <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/lifelong-learning.html">Continuous machine Learning</a>, and <i>Meta-learning</i> is part of it too. 
<li>Learn like humans - retain the knowledge learned in the past and use it to help future learning to build a lifelong learning machine
<li> <font color=#ff0000>Second edition</font>: <a href="https://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/lifelong-machine-learning.html">Lifelong Machine Learning</a>, Morgan & Claypool publishers, 207 pages, Aug 2018 (1st edition, November 2016), 
<li> <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/IJCAI15-tutorial.html">Lifelong Machine Learning Tutorial</a>, IJCAI-2015, July 25-31, 2015, Buenos Aires, Argentina
</ul>
<li><b><a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/open-classification.html">Open World Machine Learning or Classification</a></b>: one form of <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/lifelong-learning.html">Lifelong Learning</a>
<ul>
<li>Identify unseen classes during testing or application and incrementally learn them. 
<li><i>Closed world assumption</i>: classic machine learning assumes that test instances must be from training classes. Not true in open or dynamic environments. 
<li> A chatbot or self-driving car cannot learn during chatting or driving in the open envoronment is not intelligent.
</ul>
<li><b><a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/continuous-learning-chatbot.html">Continuous Learning in Chatbots</a></b>
<ul> 
<li>See this 2018 paper "<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1802.06024">Towards a Continuous Knowledge Learning Engine for Chatbots</a>."
</ul>
<li><b><a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/intention-mining.html">Intent Mining - Mining user Intents or Intentions in Social Media Posts</a></b>
<ul> 
<li>Chapter 11 of my <a href="https://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/FBS/sentiment-opinion-emotion-analysis.html">sentiment analysis</a> book discusses this topic; also see this <a href="https://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/NAACL-2013-Zhiyuan-Intention.pdf">NAACL-HLT-2013</a> paper.
</ul>
<li> <b><a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/NSF/PSC-IIS-0307239.html"> PU Learning - Learning from Positive and Unlabeled Examples</a></b> (<b>Set Expansion</b> is also a PU learning problem) <!-- Papers: ICML-02, ICML-03, IJCAI-03, ICDM-03--></li>
<ul>
<!--<li> Two applications: (1) extract what you want, and (2) make real discoveries -->
<LI> Download our LPU system - <A HREF="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/LPU/LPU-download.html"> <font color=#ff0000>LPU</font></A> and Spy-EM (S-EM) system - <A HREF="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/S-EM/S-EM-download.html"> <font color=#ff0000>S-EM </font> </A>
</ul>
<li> <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/FBS/fake-reviews.html"> <b>Detect Fake Reviews and Fake Reviewers - Detect Opinion Spam</b></a>
<ul>
<li> Detecting fake or deceptive opinions on review sites, facebook, Twitter, Weibo, and forum discussion sites
</ul>
<li> <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/Synthesize/orgSynthesize.html"><b> Generate a Book Automatically</b>: Synthesize knowledge on the Web</a> (See our <a href="https://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/WWW-2003.pdf">WWW-2003 paper</a>).
<ul>
<li> Given a topic, discover sub-topics and related concepts, and 
synthesize information from multiple Web pages to present a coherent and 
complete picture of the topic. It is like generating a "book" on the topic. 
</ul>
<!-- <ul>
<li> (1) Extract product features that have been commented on by customers and determine their opinons in product reviews. (2) Extract and analyze comparative sentences in reviews, forum and blog posts. 
</ul> -->
<!-- <li> <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/papers_topics.html#web">Comparing Web sites to find competitive intelligence information</a> - Papers: WWW-02, KDD-01. -->
<li> <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/WebDataExtraction/dataExtract.html"> Web Data Extraction from Flat/Nested Data Records</a> - <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/WebClean/webClean.html">Web page template detection and noise removal</a><!-- -- Papers: IJCAI-03, KDD-03 --> 
<ul>
<li> Download <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/WebDataExtraction/MDR-download.html"><font color=#ff0000>MDR</font></a>; Two new
systems are <font color=#ff0000>DEPTA</font> and <font color=#ff0000>NET</font>.
</ul>
<!--<LI> <A href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/TempSearch/tempSearch.html">Temporal dimension of search</a>
<LI> <A href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/CLTC/crossLangTextCl.html">Cross language text classification</a> -->
<!-- <li>Compare two competitors' Web sites to find similarities and differences (WWW-02, KDD-01)
</ul> 
<li> <b><a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/papers_topics.html#web">Web Data Mining</b></a>
-->
<LI> <b><A href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/papers_topics.html#cba">Data Mining and Knowledge Discovery</a></b>
<ul>
<li> <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/diagnosticDM/diagnosticDM.html">
<b>Diagnostic Data Mining</b></a> - <font color="red">Interestingness of Knowledge</font><b>:</b> Finding interesting and actionable knowledge.
<ul>
<li> We built a system in 2006, called <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/diagnosticDM/OM.JPG">Opportunity Map
</a> (also known as OM in Motorola). It was deployed in 2006 and is still
in regular use in Motorola. <!--Additional funding has been made available 
by Motorola to support this research for another two years (2007 and 2008).--> Motorola has sold copies of the system to some Telco companies. There is also a patent, but unfortunately it is owned by Motorola, not us :-(. 
</ul>

<LI> <b><A HREF="http://www.comp.nus.edu.sg/~dm2">
Classification Based on Associations - Integrating Classification and Association Rule Mining</A></b>
<ul><LI> Download <A HREF="http://www.comp.nus.edu.sg/~dm2"> 
CBA - asociation rules based classification</A>. You can also use the 
<A href="http://www.csc.liv.ac.uk/~frans/KDD/Software/CBA/cba.html"><font color="red">CBA implementation</font></a> of Frans Coenen from Univesity of Livepool. 
<li> <A HREF="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/kdd98_1.ps"> 
KDD-98 paper </a> and <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/papers_topics.html#cba">others</a> (KDD-99, PKDD-00, etc)
</ul>
<LI> <b><A HREF="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/papers_topics.html#assoc"> Association rule mining with multiple minimum supports</b></a> 
<li> <b><A HREF="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/papers_topics.html#interestingness"> Interestingness:</a> </b><A href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/papers_topics.html#subj">subjective interestingness</a>, <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/papers_topics.html#summary"> rule summary</a>, <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/papers_topics.html#query"> rule query language</a>, <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/papers_topics.html#change">change mining</a>
</UL>
</ul>

